        <!--ADD CONTENT HERE-->
        <h4 class="assign"> Tuesday, 2/6/18: </h4>
        <h4>Once you have determined the style for a website using the
          template page and internal style, create an external style
          sheet and move the style code into it.</h4>
        <p>Create some organizational/layout structure using a layout table and different headings on the page. Use all three of the following forms of style sheets in 3 html pages: External style sheet, Internal style sheet/s, Inline style sheet.

In at least 1 of the pages, use all 3 kinds of style so that you can see how they cascade, which style is applied when 2 or more are giving different style directions.

Link all 3 pages to the external style sheet.

Demonstrate that you know how to use classes effectively
</p>
        <ul>
          <li><a href="http://www.w3schools.com/css/css_howto.asp">Create
              an external style sheet in notepad</a></li>
          <li>Remember to save it with a .css file extension</li>
          <li> Link all pages that will use that style sheet to it using
            this link: <br>
            <br>
            &lt;link rel="stylesheet" type="text/css"
            href="tutorial.css" / &gt;</li>
        </ul>
        <h4>
          In the style sheet set the code for the following:
        </h4>
        <ul>
          <li>Background: image or color</li>
          <li>Text: color, alignment, background-color and line-height</li>
          <li>Font: family, size, style, variant and boldness </li>
          <li>Border: look at all border properties, but learn bottom
            border in particular</li>
          <li>Margin: left, right, top and bottom </li>
          <li>Padding: left, right, top and bottom </li>
          <li>Lists: different markers in ordered and unordered lists;
            set an image as the list-item marker</li>
          <li>Pseudo-classes: set the color for these states of
            hyperlinks: link, visited, hover</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
